{
	"info": {
		"name": "hotel-sim · core-api (linear, real webhooks)",
		"_postman_id": "a7e1c2d4-0000-4000-9000-hotelsim00001",
		"description": "Single linear journey for hotel-sim. **Run top to bottom on the smoke profile.**\n\nFolders 00–03 are the booking spine (health → customer → availability → folio). From folder 04 onward, every payment state change is driven by a **real payments-sim trigger** — the sim mints `pspReference` and fires its own signed webhook back to core-api. **No webhooks are hand-fired on the happy path**, so there is exactly one `pspReference` and only the sim ever sets it; the folder-04 desync footgun is gone.\n\n**Prereq stack (real loop needs the test-trigger router reachable):**\n```\ndocker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.smoke.yml up -d\ndocker compose exec -T db psql -U hotelops -d hotelops < seed-products.sql\n```\n\n**Topology:** from your host you hit core-api at `{{baseUrl}}` (8080) and payments-sim at `{{pspBaseUrl}}` (8081). The sim calls core-api back over the docker-internal name `core-api:8080`, so the loop completes inside compose. `?sync=true` on every trigger dispatches the webhook inline — no sleeps; the next read reflects the new state.\n\nFolder 06 holds invariant probes (expected failures). Two of them POST a raw webhook on purpose: they test core-api's webhook **receiver** contract (bad signature; duplicate replay) for events the well-behaved sim will not produce. Those are receiver-contract probes, not state transitions.",
		"schema": "https://schema.getpostman.com/json/collection/v2.1.0/collection.json"
	},
